    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "Can the Honey Tour robot actually follow my pet?", a: "Yes — the robot uses motion detection and can be remotely controlled via the app. It drives on two treads that handle hardwood, tile, and low-pile carpet. Cats especially tend to be curious about it (sometimes too curious — expect some batting at the camera). For dogs, it works best when they're calm and not trying to play with it." },
      { q: "Does the Honey Tour robot camera get stuck?", a: "It can get stuck on thick rugs, door thresholds over 1cm, and loose cables. It's best suited for homes with mostly hard floors. The robot is smart enough to avoid walls but not smart enough to navigate complex obstacle courses. Think of it as a remote-control car with a camera, not a Roomba." },
      { q: "Is the 4.7★ rating real with only 300+ reviews?", a: "The rating is high because early adopters love the concept and execution. With only 320 reviews, it's a newer product and the sample size is small. The rating may settle around 4.3-4.5 as more reviews come in. That said, the product delivers on its core promise — a movable camera that follows your pet." },
